Q1

Both \(\boldsymbol{R}_1\) and \(\boldsymbol{R}_2\) are the Cholesky factor of the pd matrix \(\boldsymbol{X}^T \boldsymbol{X}\), which we have shown (by induction) to be unique. Therefore \(\boldsymbol{R}_1 = \boldsymbol{R}_2\) and \(\boldsymbol{Q}_1 = \boldsymbol{X} \boldsymbol{R}_1^{-1} = \boldsymbol{X} \boldsymbol{R}_2^{-1} = \boldsymbol{Q}_2\).

Q2

Let \(\boldsymbol{X} = \boldsymbol{U} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{V}^T\) be the thin SVD of design matrix. Then the ridge solution at \(\lambda\) is
\[ \begin{eqnarray*} \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} (\lambda) &=& (\boldsymbol{V} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}^2 \boldsymbol{V}^T + \lambda \boldsymbol{I}_p)^{-1} \boldsymbol{V} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{U} \boldsymbol{y} \\ &=& [\boldsymbol{V} (\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^2 + \lambda \boldsymbol{I}_p) \boldsymbol{V}^T]^{-1} \boldsymbol{V} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{U}^T \boldsymbol{y} \\ &=& \boldsymbol{V} (\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^2 + \lambda \boldsymbol{I}_p)^{-1} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{U}^T \boldsymbol{y} \\ &=& \sum_{i=1}^r \frac{\sigma_i \boldsymbol{u}_i^T \boldsymbol{y}}{\sigma_i^2 + \lambda} \boldsymbol{v}_i \end{eqnarray*} \]
with squared \(\ell_2\) norm
\[ \|\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} (\lambda)\|_2^2 = \sum_{i=1}^r \left( \frac{\sigma_i \boldsymbol{u}_i^T \boldsymbol{y}}{\sigma_i^2 + \lambda} \right)^2. \]
Each summand is decreasing in \(\lambda\), so is \(\|\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} (\lambda)\|_2\).

The fitted values at \(\lambda\) is
\[ \begin{eqnarray*} \hat{\boldsymbol{y}} (\lambda) &=& \boldsymbol{X} \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} (\lambda) \\ &=& \boldsymbol{U} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} (\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^2 + \lambda \boldsymbol{I}_p)^{-1} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{U}^T \boldsymbol{y} \\ &=& \sum_{i=1}^r \frac{\sigma_i^2 \boldsymbol{u}_i^T \boldsymbol{y}}{\sigma_i^2 + \lambda} \boldsymbol{u}_i \end{eqnarray*} \] with squared \(\ell_2\) norm \[ \|\hat{\boldsymbol{y}} (\lambda)\|_2^2 = \sum_{i=1}^r \left( \frac{\sigma_i^2 \boldsymbol{u}_i^T \boldsymbol{y}}{\sigma_i^2 + \lambda} \right)^2. \] Again each summand is decreasing in \(\lambda\), so is \(\|\hat{\boldsymbol{y}} (\lambda)\|_2\).

The residual vector at \(\lambda\) is \[ \begin{eqnarray*} \hat{\boldsymbol{r}} (\lambda) &=& \boldsymbol{y} - \boldsymbol{X} \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} (\lambda) \\ &=& \left[ \boldsymbol{I}_n - \boldsymbol{U} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} (\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^2 + \lambda \boldsymbol{I}_p)^{-1} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{U}^T \right] \boldsymbol{y} \\ &=& \boldsymbol{U} [\boldsymbol{I}_n - \boldsymbol{\Sigma} (\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^2 + \lambda \boldsymbol{I}_p)^{-1} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}] \boldsymbol{U}^T \boldsymbol{y} \\ &=& \sum_{i=1}^r \frac{\boldsymbol{u}_i^T \boldsymbol{y}}{\sigma_i^2/\lambda + 1} \boldsymbol{u}_i \end{eqnarray*} \] with squared \(\ell_2\) norm
\[ \|\hat{\boldsymbol{r}} (\lambda)\|_2^2 = \sum_{i=1}^r \left( \frac{\boldsymbol{u}_i^T \boldsymbol{y}}{\sigma_i^2/\lambda + 1} \right)^2. \] We see each summand here is increasing in \(\lambda\), so is \(\|\hat{\boldsymbol{r}} (\lambda)\|_2\).

Here is a simple function for ridge regression

#' Ridge regression
#'
#' \code{ridge.svd} implements the ridge regression using SVD
#'
#' @param y a length n response vector
#' @param X an n-by-p predictor matrix
#' @param lambda a vector of nonnegative tuning parameter values
#' @return a list that contains: 
#'  betahat, ridge solution at each lambda values
#'  yhat, fitted values at each lambda values
#'  resid, residual vector at each lambda values
#' @seealso 
ridge.svd <- function(y, X, lambda) { 
  
  # check dimension
  if (dim(X)[1] != length(y))
    stop("X and y should have same number of obs.")
  
  # check nonnegativity of lambda
  if (any(lambda < 0))
    stop("tuning parameter lambda should be nonnegative")
  
  # pre-compute SVD of X and t(U) %*% y
  xsvd <- svd(X)
  uty <- as.vector(crossprod(xsvd$u, y))
  
  # M contains entries sigma_i / (sigma_i^2 + \lambda_j)
  M <- outer(xsvd$d, lambda, function(a, b) a / (a^2 + b))
  # ridge solution at all lambda
  betahat <- xsvd$v %*% (M * uty)
  # fitted values
  yhat <- xsvd$u %*% (M * (uty * xsvd$d))
  # residuals
  resid <- y - yhat
  
  # output
  list(betahat = betahat, yhat = yhat, resid = resid)
  
  }

qplot(lambda, residl2, xlab = expression(lambda),

Q3

This is a classical problem known as Procrustes transformation, which is widely used to align images or shapes before statistical analysis. To know more about this problem, read Section 14.5.1 of Elements of Statistical Learning (ESL) or the paper by Goodall.

Procrustes was an African bandit in Greek mythology, who stretched or squashed his visitors to fit his iron bed (eventually killing them).

  1. Expand the Procrustes criterion, we obtain
    \[ \begin{eqnarray*} & & \|\boldsymbol{X} - (\beta \boldsymbol{Y} \boldsymbol{O} + \boldsymbol{1}_n \boldsymbol{\mu}^T)\|_F^2 \\ &=& \text{tr}(\boldsymbol{X}^T \boldsymbol{X}) - 2 \text{tr}(\boldsymbol{X}^T(\beta \boldsymbol{Y} \boldsymbol{O} + \boldsymbol{1}_n \boldsymbol{\mu}^T)) + \text{tr}((\beta \boldsymbol{Y} \boldsymbol{O} + \boldsymbol{1}_n \boldsymbol{\mu}^T)^T(\beta \boldsymbol{Y} \boldsymbol{O} + \boldsymbol{1}_n \boldsymbol{\mu}^T)) \\ &=& \text{tr}(\boldsymbol{X}^T \boldsymbol{X}) + \beta^2 \text{tr}(\boldsymbol{Y}^T \boldsymbol{Y}) + n \boldsymbol{\mu}^T \boldsymbol{\mu} + 2 \beta \boldsymbol{\mu}^T \boldsymbol{O}^T \boldsymbol{Y}^T \boldsymbol{1}_n - 2 \beta \text{tr}(\boldsymbol{X}^T \boldsymbol{Y} \boldsymbol{O}) - 2 \boldsymbol{\mu}^T \boldsymbol{X}^T \boldsymbol{1}_n. \end{eqnarray*} \] Setting the partial derivatives with respect to \(\boldsymbol{\mu}\) gives the stationarity condition \[ 2n \boldsymbol{\mu} + 2 \beta \boldsymbol{O}^T \boldsymbol{Y}^T \boldsymbol{1}_n - 2 \boldsymbol{X}^T \boldsymbol{1}_n = \boldsymbol{0}_p, \] which implies that the optimal point satisfies \[ \boldsymbol{\mu} = n^{-1} \boldsymbol{X}^T \boldsymbol{1}_n - n^{-1} \beta \boldsymbol{O}^T \boldsymbol{Y}^T \boldsymbol{1}_n = \boldsymbol{\bar x} - \beta \boldsymbol{O}^T \boldsymbol{\bar y}. \] Substitution to the original criterion, we see \[ \|\boldsymbol{X} - (\beta \boldsymbol{Y} \boldsymbol{O} + \boldsymbol{1}_n \boldsymbol{\mu}^T)\|_F^2 = \|(\boldsymbol{X} - \boldsymbol{1} \boldsymbol{\bar x}^T) - \beta (\boldsymbol{Y} - \boldsymbol{1}_n \boldsymbol{\bar y}^T) \boldsymbol{O} \|_F^2 = \| \boldsymbol{\tilde X} - \beta \boldsymbol{\tilde Y} \boldsymbol{O}\|_F^2. \] Therefore we can always first (column) center both matrices and then do not need to consider shifting.

  2. Writing \[ \| \boldsymbol{\tilde X} - \beta \boldsymbol{\tilde Y} \boldsymbol{O}\|_F^2 = \text{tr}(\boldsymbol{\tilde X}^T \boldsymbol{\tilde X}) - 2 \beta \text{tr}(\boldsymbol{O}^T \boldsymbol{\tilde Y}^T \boldsymbol{\tilde X}) + \beta^2 \text{tr}(\boldsymbol{\tilde Y}^T \boldsymbol{\tilde Y}), \] we need to maximize the term \(\text{tr}(\boldsymbol{O}^T \boldsymbol{\tilde Y}^T \boldsymbol{\tilde X})\). Let the SVD of \(\boldsymbol{\tilde Y}^T \boldsymbol{\tilde X}\) be \(\boldsymbol{U} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{V}^T\). Then \[ \text{tr}(\boldsymbol{O}^T \boldsymbol{\tilde Y}^T \boldsymbol{\tilde X}) = \text{tr}(\boldsymbol{O}^T \boldsymbol{U} \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{V}^T) = \text{tr}(\boldsymbol{V}^T \boldsymbol{O}^T \boldsymbol{U} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}) = \text{tr}(\boldsymbol{Z} \boldsymbol{\Sigma}) = \sum_i z_{ii} \sigma_i \le \sum_i \sigma_i, \] where \(Z = \boldsymbol{V}^T \boldsymbol{O}^T \boldsymbol{U}\) is orthogonal and thus all its entries have magnitude \(\le 1\). Taking \(\boldsymbol{\hat O} = \boldsymbol{U} \boldsymbol{V}^T\) apparently achieves the maximum value \(\sum_i \sigma_i = \text{tr}(\boldsymbol{\Sigma})\). Then optimal \(\beta\) is \(\hat \beta = \text{tr}(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}) / \|\boldsymbol{\tilde Y}\|_F^2\).

  3. Above analysis suggests the optimal solution \[ \begin{eqnarray*} \boldsymbol{\hat O} &=& \boldsymbol{U} \boldsymbol{V}^T \\ \hat \beta &=& \text{tr}(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}) / \|\boldsymbol{\tilde Y}\|_F^2 \\ \boldsymbol{\hat \mu} &=& \boldsymbol{\bar x} - \hat \beta \boldsymbol{\hat O}^T \boldsymbol{\bar y}, \end{eqnarray*} \] which is straightforward to implement using SVD. We write a procrustes function for computing the optimal Procrustes rotation.

#' Procurstes rotation for matching two matrices
#'
#' \code{procrustes} implements the Procrustes rotation method
#'
#' @param X an n-by-p matrix, the target shape
#' @param Y an n-by-p matrix, the shape to rotate
#' @return a list that contains: 
#'  beta, a positive scaling factor
#'  O, a p-by-p orthogonal matrix
#'  mu, a p-by-1 vector of shift
#'  Z, the n-by-p resulting shape rotated from Y
#'  d, the Procrustes distance
#' @seealso 
procrustes <- function(X, Y) { 
  
  # check dimension
  if (dim(X)[1] != dim(Y)[1] || dim(X)[2] != dim(Y)[2])
    stop("X and Y should be matrices of same size")
  
  # center X and Y
  Xc <- scale(X, center = TRUE, scale = FALSE)
  Yc <- scale(Y, center = TRUE, scale = FALSE)
  
  # SVD of t(Yc) %*% Xc
  ytxsvd <- svd(crossprod(Yc, Xc))
  
  # collect results
  beta <- as.numeric(sum(ytxsvd$d) / norm(Yc, "F")^2)
  O <- tcrossprod(ytxsvd$u, ytxsvd$v)
  mu <- attr(Xc, "scaled:center") - 
    beta * crossprod(O, attr(Yc, "scaled:center"))
  Z <- beta * (Y %*% O) + rep(mu, each = dim(X)[1])
  d <- norm(X - Z, "F")
  
  # output
  list(beta = beta, O = O, mu = mu, Z = Z, d = d)
  
  }

library(ggplot2)
# read the two 3s data
X <- read.table("http://hua-zhou.github.io/teaching/st758-2014fall/X.txt", 
                sep = ",")

                sep = ",")
Y <- as.matrix(Y)
# compute the Procrustes rotation
Z <- procrustes(X, Y)$Z
ggplot(data = data.frame(X, Y, Z)) + 
  geom_path(aes(x = X[, 1], y = X[, 2]), colour = "red") + 
  geom_path(aes(x = Y[, 1], y = Y[, 2]), colour = "blue") + 
  geom_path(aes(x = Z[, 1], y = Z[, 2]), colour = "grey", linetype = 11) + 
  xlab("") + ylab("")
